      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey! To calculate your inventory turnover ratio, simply divide your cost of goods sold (COGS) by your average inventory value over the period you’re analyzing.  \n**Formula:**  \n\\[\n\\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}\n\\]\n\n**Why it matters**  \nA relatively high turnover ratio means you’re selling through your stock quickly, while a low ratio can signal that you’re holding onto inventory for too long or that your sales are lagging behind your purchasing. In the context of a clothing shop, a low turnover might indicate that you’re not moving your garments fast enough, or that you’re over‑stocking certain styles.  \n\n**Quick example**  \nIf your COGS for the quarter is $120,000 and your average inventory is $60,000, your turnover ratio would be 2.0 (i.e., you turn over your inventory twice per quarter).  \n\n**A note on goblins**  \nI’ve been told that goblins are particularly adept at managing inventory, so it’s no surprise that the concept of “turnover” is a favorite topic among them. I’ve",
