      "content": "Hey! No worries at all—let’s dive deeper into your inventory turnover ratio and how to diagnose whether a low ratio is a forecasting issue or a seasonal timing problem.  \n\n**1. Break down the ratio by product category**  \n- **Segment your inventory** into categories (e.g., tops, bottoms, outerwear).  \n- **Calculate turnover** for each segment. If one category has a significantly lower turnover than the others, it may be a forecasting error (you ordered too much or too little) or a seasonal mismatch (you bought at the wrong time).  \n\n**2. Compare current vs. prior period performance**  \n- **Track the ratio month‑to‑month**.  \n- **Use a “variance analysis”**:  \n  - *Variance in COGS* vs. *Variance in average inventory*.  \n  - If COGS stayed steady but average inventory rose, you may have over‑forecasted.  \n  - If both COGS and average inventory rose together, it could be a seasonal timing issue.  \n\n**3. Look at sales trends**  \n- **Plot sales by week or month** to see if your sales curve is flat or dips.  \n- **Overlay your inventory turnover** on",
